# Range `..` and index `^` operators

Use range and index operators for slicing arrays, strings, spans, and any indexable collection — instead of arithmetic on `Length` / `Count` or `Substring(...)`.

## Preferred

```csharp
char last = name[^1];
string withoutLastTwo = name[..^2];
string suffix = path[(path.LastIndexOf('/') + 1)..];

ReadOnlySpan<byte> body = packet[HeaderSize..];
ReadOnlySpan<byte> head = packet[..HeaderSize];
```

## Avoid

```csharp
// Avoid
char last = name[name.Length - 1];
string withoutLastTwo = name.Substring(0, name.Length - 2);
ReadOnlySpan<byte> body = packet.Slice(HeaderSize);
```

## Scope

- Use `^n` for "from the end" instead of `Length - n`.
- Use `a..b`, `..b`, `a..` for slices instead of `Substring`, `.Take`, `.Skip`, or `.Slice`.
- Watch for off-by-one: `..^2` drops the last **two** elements; `..^0` is the whole sequence.
- For `IEnumerable<T>` (no indexer), continue to use LINQ — these operators are for indexable types.
